CERTIFICATE OF CONCURRENCE This is to certify that Indiana Michigan Power Company ("I&M"), assents to and concurs in the FERC FPA Electric Tariffs described below, which Appalachian Power Company ("APCo"), the designated filing company, has filed in its "APCo Rate Schedules and Service Agreements Tariffs" database. 1. Name of Tariff Adopted by Reference: Reactive Supply and Voltage Control from Generation Service APCO Tariff Record Adopted by Reference: Rate Schedule No. 304, Reactive Supply and Voltage Control from Generation Service Description of Tariff: Rate Schedule under which APCo, I&M, and Kentucky Power Company coordinate the allocation of the revenue requirements for the provision of Reactive Supply Service to PJM, as contemplated by Schedule 2 of the PJM open access transmission tariff. This Rate Schedule shall be effective upon the date authorized by the Federal Energy Regulatory Commission.
By: /John C. Crespo/ John C. Crespo, Deputy General Counsel - Regulatory Services Dated: June 14, 2013

Operations Agreement between Indiana Michigan Power Company and Wabash Valley Power Association, Inc. Tariff Submitter: Indiana Michigan Power Company FERC Tariff Program Name: FERC FPA Electric Tariff Tariff Title: RS and SA Tariff Record Proposed Effective Date: January 1, 2021 Record Content Description: SA#817 Tariff Record Title: I&M-WVPA Operations Agreement Option Code: AOPERATIONS AGREEMENT This Operations Agreement (the Agreement) is entered into as of July 30, 2020 between Indiana Michigan Power Company, an Indiana corporation (I&M) and Wabash Valley Power Association, Inc., an Indiana nonprofit corporation (Wabash). For purposes of this Agreement, I&M and Wabash shall each be referred to as a Party and collectively as the Parties. RECITALS A. Wabash owns the 345 kV Meridian Substation located in Whitley County, Indiana interconnected to I&Ms Sorenson to Twin Branch 345 kV line on the Transmission System (the Meridian Substation). B. I&M provides certain operations and maintenance services to Wabash related to the Meridian Substation pursuant to that certain Repair and Operations Agreement between I&M and Wabash dated December 11, 1989 (1989 O&M Agreement). I&M has exercised its right to terminate the 1989 O&M Agreement effective as of December 31, 2020. C. Wabash has registered with NERC, the Regional Entity, and PJM Interconnection, L.L.C. (PJM) as a Transmission Owner with respect to the Meridian Substation, giving rise to additional regulatory and compliance obligations. D. Wabash desires I&M to perform the Operations Services (as defined herein) and provide Compliance Support Services (as further described in an Addendum to this Agreement executed by the Parties and attached as Exhibit C) for the Meridian Substation, and I&M is willing to perform such activities upon the terms and conditions set forth in this Agreement. AGREEMENTS NOW, THEREFORE, the Parties hereby agree as follows: 1. DEFINITIONS; RULES OF CONSTRUCTION 1.1. Definitions. As used in this Agreement, terms defined in Exhibit A have the meanings set forth therein. 1.2. Rules of Construction. Unless the context of this Agreement requires otherwise, the plural includes the singular, and the singular includes the plural. The words include, includes and including are not limiting and have the inclusive meaning of including without limitation. The words hereof, herein, hereby, hereunder and other similar terms of this Agreement refer to this Agreement as a whole and not exclusively to any particular provision of this Agreement. All pronouns and any variations thereof will be deemed to refer to masculine, feminine, or neuter, singular, or plural, as the identity of the Person or Persons may require. Unless otherwise expressly Page 1 provided, any agreement, instrument, or Applicable Law defined or referred to herein means such agreement or instrument or Applicable Law as from time to time amended, modified, or supplemented, including (in the case of agreements or instruments) by waiver or consent and (in the case of Applicable Law) by succession of comparable successor law and includes (in the case of agreements or instruments) references to all attachments thereto and instruments incorporated therein. A reference to a Party includes its successors and permitted assigns. This Agreement is the result of negotiations between, and has been reviewed by, the Parties, and their respective counsel have had the opportunity to review this Agreement. Accordingly, this Agreement will be deemed to be the product of all Parties hereto, and no ambiguity will be construed in favor of or against any Party. 2. TERM AND TERMINATION 2.1. Effective Date and Term. This Agreement has been accepted for filing and made effective by order of the Commission under the Federal Power Act, in which case the effective date of this Agreement shall be as specified in the said Commission order (the Effective Date). The Parties shall request that the Agreement become effective as of January 1, 2021. Each Party shall use its commercially reasonable efforts to take or cause to be taken all action requisite to the end that this Agreement shall become effective on January 1, 2021 or at the earliest practicable date thereafter. Subject to termination pursuant to Section 2.2, the term of this Agreement shall be five (5) years from the Effective Date (Term). Thereafter, this Agreement shall automatically renew for successive terms of one (1) year each unless either Party elects to terminate the Agreement by providing written notice of termination to the other Party at least three hundred sixty-five (365) calendar days prior to the start of any renewal term. 2.2. Events of Termination. This Agreement may be terminated by the Parties as follows: 2.2.1. Either Party may terminate this Agreement for an Event of Default as provided in Section 5.2. 2.2.2. This Agreement may be terminated by mutual written agreement of the Parties. 2.2.3. I&M will submit a notice of termination with FERC to effectuate any termination. 3. SERVICES 3.1. Services. 3.1.1. Operations Services. Subject to the terms and conditions of this Agreement, I&M will perform the operations services for the Meridian Substation set forth in Exhibit B (the Operations Services). I&M shall provide the personnel, tools, and equipment that I&M deems necessary or advisable in connection with the Operations Services. Page 2 3.1.2. Compliance Support Services. Subject to the terms and conditions of this Agreement, I&M will perform the services described in Exhibit C Addendum for NERC Compliance Support (the Compliance Support Services) in support of Wabashs performance of certain of its obligations under the NERC Reliability Standards (Compliance Obligations) arising from Wabash registering as the Transmission Owner with respect to the Meridian Substation. 3.1.3. Emergencies. If I&M believes in good faith that a condition or circumstance that threatens imminent harm to Persons, property or the environment exists or has occurred or that the performance of any of the Operations Services would (in the reasonable judgment of I&M) create an unreasonable safety risk to Persons, property or the environment, or would violate the safety policies or procedures of I&M or any AEP Resources (each of the foregoing, an Emergency), I&M may take such actions, or cause such actions to be taken, that in I&Ms sole judgment, are reasonably required to avoid or mitigate the Emergency without the need for prior notice to or approval by Wabash. I&M will provide Notice to Wabash as soon as reasonably practicable of any action taken in response to any Emergency under this Section 3.1.3. 3.1.4. Operations Scope Limitation. Wabash agrees that it is responsible for all activities with respect to the Meridian Substation that are not described in Exhibit B, including, without limitation, maintenance on the Meridian Substation, operations services not described in Exhibit B, security of the site, erosion control, station service (primary and backup), and containment (gas and other chemicals). 3.1.5. Compliance Scope Limitation. Wabash agrees that I&Ms responsibilities with respect to the Compliance Support Services are limited to those set forth in Exhibit C and shall not include any responsibility for performing the Wabash Compliance Obligations. 3.1.6. Changes to Scope. The Parties may amend the scope of the Operations Services or the Compliance Support Services pursuant to an amendment of this Agreement under Section 11.4. 3.2. Standards of Performance. I&M shall perform the Operations Services and Compliance Support Services in accordance with Good Utility Practice and Applicable Law. Subject to the foregoing, I&M shall perform the Operations Services and Compliance Support Services in accordance with the same standards and procedures it utilizes to perform such services for its own facilities. Wabash shall not be responsible for claims or penalties arising from I&Ms violation of Applicable Law in providing the Operations Services and Compliance Support Services unless I&M is acting pursuant to direction from Wabash. Page 3 3.3. Use of Resources. I&M may perform the Operations Services or the Compliance Support Services under this Agreement by using subcontractors, suppliers, and consultants, and personnel from its Affiliates (collectively, the AEP Resources). I&M will be solely responsible for the supervision, direction, and control of all of the AEP Resources engaged in the performance of the Operations Services or the Compliance Support Services and such personnel will be employees or independent contractors of I&M and not of Wabash. I&M will be responsible for the payment of all compensation, benefits, and employment taxes with respect to the services of the AEP Resources. I&M will have the right to remove, reassign, or take any other employment-related action in regard to any of the AEP Resources. I&M shall cause each I&M Resource performing the Operations Services or the Compliance Support Services under this Agreement to comply with the terms and conditions of this Agreement, but only I&M shall be liable under this Agreement for the performance of the obligations under this Agreement regardless of I&Ms reliance on AEP Resources. 3.4. Cooperation. Wabash will coordinate its activities with respect to the Meridian Substation with the facilities of I&M and the AEP Resources, and will generally cooperate with all such parties so as to minimize delays, errors, inconsistencies, changes, and unnecessary costs to perform the Operations Services; provided, however, that Wabash shall not be obligated to act contrary to Good Utility Practice in providing such cooperation. 3.5. Access. Wabash grants I&M and the AEP Resources access rights to the Meridian Substation, and the use of and the right to occupy such physical space associated with the Meridian Substation at all times during the Term as may be reasonably necessary or convenient to I&M to perform the Operations Services. I&M shall have the right to maintain RTU/SCADA communication links to its existing RTU, in order to perform remote switching and have situational awareness of current operational conditions within Meridian Station. 3.6. Owner Instructions. At any time, I&M may, if it deems it to be reasonably necessary or appropriate, request and receive detailed instructions (or clarifications of directives) from Wabash prior to taking any action with respect to the Operations Services. I&M may defer action pending the receipt of such written instructions. Wabash agrees that it will not unreasonably withhold or delay any instruction or direction to I&M that is necessary to enable I&M to provide the Operations Services. 3.7. Compliance with Reliability Standards. Wabash shall be solely responsible for the maintenance of the Meridian Substation. As specifically set forth in Exhibit C, I&M shall perform the Compliance Support Services. I&M shall not be required to register as transmission owner, transmission operator, transmission planner, or any other applicable function with respect to the Meridian Substation. I&M is not required to make any filings with NERC or any other Governmental Authority on behalf of Wabash with respect to the Meridian Substation, but as set forth in Exhibit C, I&M shall provide Wabash with such records, information and documents directly related to the Meridian Substation as reasonably necessary for Wabash to perform the Compliance Obligations. Page 4 3.8. Responsibility for Compliance Obligations. I&M shall not be responsible for any penalty or fine associated with non-compliance with the Compliance Obligations imposed as a result of a self-report, or a Governmental Authority audit, investigation, or proceeding related to the Meridian Substation. 4. COSTS; INVOICING; TAXES 4.1. Responsibility for Costs. 4.1.1. Wabash agrees to pay to I&M the Monthly Delivery Point Charge in exchange for I&M performing the Operations Services and the Compliance Support Services. 4.1.2. Wabash will be responsible for all capital costs associated with the Meridian Substation. 4.1.3. All costs reasonably incurred for all actions taken by I&M and AEP Resources to avoid or mitigate an Emergency in regard to the Meridian Station in accordance with Section 3.1.3 will be paid or reimbursed by Wabash. 4.2. Invoices. 4.2.1. Not later than 30 Calendar Days after the end of each month during the Term, I&M will deliver to Wabash an invoice which will show the monthly charges payable by Wabash for the month and payment will be made by Wabash no later than 30 Calendar Days after the date the invoice is received by Wabash. 4.2.2. If Wabash disputes any portion of any amount specified in an invoice delivered by I&M, Wabash will pay the total amount of the invoice when due, and Wabash shall identify the disputed amount and state the basis for disputing part of the invoice amount. If it is determined that an overpayment or underpayment has been made by Wabash or the amount charged on an invoice is incorrect, then (i) in the case of any overpayment by Wabash, I&M will promptly return the amount of the overpayment (or credit the amount of the overpayment on the next invoice) to Wabash, or (ii) in the case of an underpayment by Wabash, Wabash will promptly pay the amount of the underpayment to I&M. In each case, payment will be made together with interest at the Default Rate for the period from the date of overpayment or underpayment, until such amount has been paid or credited against a future invoice. 4.3. Tax Treatment of Costs. The amounts Wabash agrees to pay I&M pursuant to Section 4.1 of this Agreement are exclusive of any state or local sales or use tax, or any other tax or similar charge. If I&M is required by Applicable Law to pay or collect any such tax, or if Wabash is required to withhold such tax, then such amount will be paid or reimbursed to I&M by Wabash. Wabash shall not be responsible to pay any federal, Page 5 state or local tax imposed on I&M and related to I&Ms receipt of monies under this Agreement. 5. DEFAULT; REMEDIES 5.1. Events of Default. An Event of Default will exist: 5.1.1. As to Wabash upon Wabashs failure to promptly pay any amount due under this Agreement within 10 Calendar Days following written notice of delinquency describing such failure in reasonable detail; or 5.1.2. As to a Party if that Party fails to commence the cure of its breach of any other obligation under this Agreement within 30 Calendar Days following written notification of such breach in reasonable detail; provided that if such failure is not capable of being cured within such 30-day period despite diligent efforts, then such 30-day period will be extended for such period as may be reasonably necessary to complete such cure with diligent efforts if the defaulting Party commences its cure within the initial 30-day period and thereafter prosecutes its cure diligently to completion. 5.1.3. A Party files a voluntary petition of bankruptcy or is adjudged bankrupt or insolvent, or has entered against it an order for relief, in any bankruptcy or insolvency proceeding. 5.2. Termination. If an Event of Default occurs as to a party described in Sections 5.1.1 or 5.1.2, then the other Party will have the right to terminate the Operations Services and the Compliance Support Services by written notice to the defaulting Party. Upon an Event of Default by a party described in Section 5.1.3, the other Party may terminate this Agreement with immediate effect by written notice to the defaulting party. 5.3. Other remedies. 5.3.1. If an Event of Default occurs and while it persists with respect to a Party, the other Party may suspend performance of its obligations under this Agreement (other than its obligations to pay money for Operations Services or Compliance Support Services provided) without prejudice to any other remedy that it may have under this Agreement or Applicable Law. 5.3.2. Whether or not a Party suspends performance of its obligations under, or terminates, this Agreement as a result of an Event of Default, Wabash will pay all amounts due, if any, for Operations Services or Compliance Support Services provided and indemnification under Article 9. 5.3.3. Subject to the limitations in Article 8, Wabash will be entitled to recover direct contract damages from I&M as a result of an Event of Default (Allowable Damages). Except as provided in this Section 5.3.3, the only other remedies for an Event of Default by I&M are either re-performance in accordance with Article 7 or termination pursuant to Section 5.2. Page 6 6. FORCE MAJEURE Neither Party will be responsible for any delay or failure to perform hereunder (other than any obligation to pay money) if such delay or failure to perform is attributable to an event of Force Majeure. In such event, the performance so affected by the Force Majeure event will be extended by a period of time corresponding to the period of time such Force Majeure event exists. In the event of an occurrence of Force Majeure, the non-performing Party shall provide written notice to the other Party within 10 Calendar Days after the occurrence of the Force Majeure event. The non-performing Party will use good faith efforts to attempt, in a commercially reasonable manner, to rectify the conditions brought about by the Force Majeure and to avoid or minimize delay. Neither Party will be required by this Agreement to settle any strike, walkout, lockout, or other labor dispute on terms which, in the sole judgment of the Party involved in the dispute, are contrary to its interest, it being understood that the settlement of strikes, walkouts, lockouts, or other labor disputes will be at the sole discretion of the party having the difficulty. Either Party will have the right to terminate this Agreement if a Force Majeure event prevents performance for more than 90 Calendar Days. 7. DISCLAIMER OF WARRANTIES THE REMEDIES CONTAINED IN THIS ARTICLE 7 AND ARTICLE 5.3.3 ARE WABASHS EXCLUSIVE REMEDIES, AND THEY ARE GIVEN AND ACCEPTED IN LIEU OF (A) ANY EXPRESS OR IMPLIED WARRANTIES BY I&M, INCLUDING WARRANTIES OF MERCHANTABILITY, FITNESS FOR A PARTICULAR PURPOSE, OR GOOD AND WORKMANLIKE PERFORMANCE, AND (B) ANY OBLIGATION, LIABILITY, RIGHT, CLAIM OR REMEDY AT LAW OR IN EQUITY ARISING OUT OF ANY DEFECT IN THE SERVICES WHETHER SUCH CLAIM ARISES UNDER CONTRACT, TORT, STRICT LIABILITY, STATUTE OR ANY OTHER LEGAL OR EQUITABLE THEORY OR PRINCIPLE INCLUDING NEGLIGENCE, GROSS NEGLIGENCE, OR WILLFUL MISCONDUCT. WITH RESPECT TO ANY DEFECT IN THE OPERATIONS SERVICES AND COMPLIANCE SUPPORT SERVICES, WABASH MAY DIRECT THAT THOSE SERVICES BE RE-PERFORMED AND IN THAT EVENT, I&M WILL BILL WABASH FOR THE RE-PERFORMANCE OF THOSE SERVICES IN ACCORDANCE WITH THIS AGREEMENT, PROVIDED, HOWEVER, THAT WITH RESPECT TO ANY DEFECT IN OPERATIONS SERVICES OR COMPLIANCE SUPPORT SERVICES RESULTING FROM THE GROSS NEGLIGENCE OR INTENTIONAL MISCONDUCT OF I&M, THOSE SERVICES WILL BE RE-PERFORMED AT I&MS SOLE COST AND EXPENSE. 8. LIMITATION OF I&MS LIABILITY; EXCLUSION OF CONSEQUENTIAL DAMAGES 8.1. Limitation of I&Ms Liability I&Ms aggregate liability for all Allowable Damages, if any, for breach of its obligations under this Agreement related to Operations Services and Compliance Page 7 Support Services rendered during any Contract Year will not exceed the excess of (a) all amounts billed by I&M for the Operations Services and Compliance Support Services rendered during the preceding Contract Year (or, where such services were rendered in the first Contract Year, during that first Contract Year) over (b) all amounts paid or payable (including taxes and other associated costs) by I&M for materials or equipment incorporated into the work in the course of the Operations Services and Compliance Support Services in that preceding Contract Year (or, where such services were rendered in the first Contract Year, during the first Contract Year). 8.2. Exclusion of Consequential Damages. Except as set forth in Article 9, neither Party will be liable under this Agreement for any special, indirect, incidental, consequential, punitive, or exemplary damages in any action arising out of this Agreement, whether based on contract, tort, or any other theory of liability. 9. INDEMNIFICATION 9.1. Indemnification for Third-Party Claims. 9.1.1. Wabash shall be liable to and will indemnify hold harmless, and defend I&M, its Affiliates, and its or their officers, employees, and agents (each an I&M Indemnified Person) for any personal injuries suffered by third parties or damage to a third partys tangible property, penalties or compliance costs imposed by any Governmental Authority, including NERC, reasonable attorney fees and other costs and expenses of defense, and (with the approval of Wabash) costs and expenses of settlement, in each case incurred by the I&M Indemnified Person, arising in connection with the Operations Services or Compliance Support Services, except to the extent such injuries or damage are caused by the gross negligence or willful misconduct of I&M or its officers, employees, agents or subcontractors. 9.1.2. I&M shall be liable to and will indemnify hold harmless, and defend Wabash, its Affiliates, and its or their officers, employees, and agents (each a Wabash Indemnified Person) for any personal injuries suffered by third parties or damage to a third partys tangible property, reasonable attorney fees and other costs and expenses of defense, and (with the approval of the Indemnifying Party) costs and expenses of settlement, in each case incurred by the Indemnified Person, arising in connection with the performance by I&M of its obligations under this Agreement and to the extent such injuries or damage are caused by the gross negligence or willful misconduct of I&M or its officers, employees, agents or subcontractors. 9.2. Notice Procedure. Each Indemnified Person must provide prompt notice of any claim for which it seeks indemnity under this provision and cooperate in defense of each such claim. Without the consent of the applicable Indemnified Persons, an Indemnifying Party may not settle any such claim for any relief (other than monetary damages) or any Page 8 claim in the nature of regulatory or similar legal enforcement action by a Governmental Authority. 9.3. Cumulative Rights. The rights and remedies provided to an Indemnified Person under this Article 9 are cumulative with any other right such Person has or may hereafter acquire under Applicable Law and any rights or remedies such Person has may be asserted completely against a Party without regard to any rights or remedies the Indemnified Person may have against any other Person. 10. CONFIDENTIALITY 10.1. Confidential Information. For purposes of this Agreement, a partys Confidential Information consists of information possessed by that Party which is confidential and commercially valuable and which is specifically identified to the other party as confidential. For purposes of this Agreement, a party (the Receiving Party) will be deemed to have received Confidential Information of the other party (the Disclosing Party) if such Confidential Information is by any means disclosed or delivered to the Receiving Party or any of its or its Affiliates equity owners, governing persons, officers, employees, advisors, attorneys, agents, or prospective or actual lenders or investors (its Representatives). Confidential Information will not include any information which the Receiving Party can demonstrate (a) has become available to the public through no breach of this Agreement; (b) was previously known by the Receiving Party without any obligation to hold it in confidence; (c) was received on a non- confidential basis from a third party free to disclose such information without restriction; or (d) was independently developed by the Receiving Party without the use of Confidential Information of the Disclosing Party. 10.2. Disclosure. Each Party hereto agrees that it shall hold in strict confidence and shall not disclose or use any Confidential Information belonging to the other Party hereto for the period ending 18 months after the date of receipt of the Confidential Information. The Receiving Party may disclose Confidential Information to its Representatives for purposes of pursuing the Work and meeting its obligations and exercising its rights hereunder, provided that the Representatives shall be informed of the confidentiality obligations provided herein. Each Party agrees to be responsible for any breach of the confidentiality obligations under this Agreement by its Representatives. 10.3. Required Disclosures. If a Party is required pursuant to Applicable Law or otherwise becomes legally compelled to disclose any of the Confidential Information or the fact that the Confidential Information has been made available to it, such Party shall (unless prohibited by Applicable Law from doing so) promptly notify the Disclosing Party in order that the Disclosing Party may seek a protective order or such other remedy as the Disclosing Party may consider appropriate in the circumstances. In any event, the compelled Party may disclose only that portion of the Confidential Information which such Party is legally required to disclose in the judgment of the Partys legal counsel without any liability to the Disclosing Party hereunder and such disclosure shall not be a breach of this Article 10. Page 9 10.4. The Receiving Party, upon written request from the Disclosing Party, shall promptly return or destroy all Confidential Information in its possession and the Receiving Party shall destroy its Evaluation Materials. If requested by the Disclosing Party, the Receiving Party shall provide the Disclosing Party with a certification that all Confidential Information and Evaluation Material have either been returned or destroyed, as applicable. The return or destruction of the Confidential Information shall not extinguish any rights or obligations under this Agreement with respect to the Confidential Information. Notwithstanding the foregoing, the Receiving Party shall not be required to purge any historical backup media and may retain may retain one or more copies of the Confidential Information solely for archival purposes and as required by applicable law 10.5. Survival. The provisions of this Article 10 shall survive a termination of this Agreement. 11. GENERAL PROVISIONS 11.1. Regulatory Filing. If I&M determines that it is required to file this Agreement with FERC, I&M will file this Agreement with FERC, and Wabash agrees to cooperate with I&M and provide reasonable assistance to I&M in such filing and proceedings related thereto. If FERC or any reviewing court, in such order or in any separate order, suspends this Agreement or any part thereof, institutes an investigation or proceeding under the provisions of the Federal Power Act, or imposes any conditions, limitation or qualifications under any of the provisions of the Federal Power Act (which individually or in the aggregate are determined by I&M or Wabash to be adverse to it), then either I&M or Wabash may terminate this Agreement upon written notice to the other Party. 11.2. Notices. Any notice that is required or permitted under this Agreement may be given by personal delivery to the Party entitled thereto, by e-mail (with confirmation of receipt), by any courier service which guarantees overnight, receipted delivery, or by U.S. Certified or Registered Mail, return receipt requested, addressed to the Party entitled thereto, at: If to Wabash: Wabash Valley Power Association, Inc. Attn: President/CEO 6702 Intech Boulevard Indianapolis, IN 46278
with copy to: Wabash Valley Power Association, Inc. Attn: General Counsel 6702 Intech Boulevard Indianapolis, IN 46278
Page 10 If to I&M: American Electric Power Service Corporation Attention: Michele Bair, Director Transmission Customer Engagement 8500 Smiths Mill Road New Albany, OH 43054 Email: mlbair@aep.com
with copy to: American Electric Power Service Corporation Attention: John W. Seidensticker, Senior Counsel 1 Riverside Plaza Columbus, OH 43215 Email: jwseidensticker@aep.com Either Party may change its address or email for notice by written notice to the other Party in accordance with this Section 11.2. Any notice given (a) by personal delivery will be deemed to be given upon such delivery, (b) by email will be deemed given upon receipt, (c) by overnight courier service will be deemed given on the date noted on the couriers receipt for delivery, or (d) by U.S. Certified or Registered Mail, return receipt requested, will be deemed given upon the date noted on such return receipt, provided, however, that if in any case delivery is made on a day other than a Business Day or after 5:00 p.m. local time on a Business Day, delivery will be deemed to be given upon the next Business Day. 11.3. Interest on Overdue Amounts. Any amount due to a Party under this Agreement will accrue interest daily from the deadline for payment thereof until paid at the Default Rate. 11.4. Amendment. This Agreement may be amended by a written instrument executed by the Parties hereto. Additionally, nothing contained herein shall be construed as affecting in any way the right of the party furnishing service under this rate schedule to unilaterally make application to FERC for a change in rates under section 205 of the Federal Power Act and pursuant to the Commissions Rules and Regulations promulgated thereunder. Nothing contained herein shall be construed as affecting in any way the right of the party receiving service under this rate schedule to unilaterally make application to FERC for a change in rates under section 206 of the Federal Power Act and pursuant to the Commissions Rules and Regulations promulgated thereunder. 11.5. Assignment. Neither Party may assign any of its rights or delegate any of its duties under this Agreement to any person without the prior written consent of the other Party, which consent will not be unreasonably withheld, conditioned, or delayed. Notwithstanding the foregoing, no consent will be required if the assignee is an Affiliate of the assigning Party, provided such Affiliate assumes all of the assigning Partys obligations and liabilities under this Agreement and agrees to be bound by this Agreement. Page 11 11.6. Merger and Integration; Binding on Successors; No Third Party Beneficiaries. This Agreement sets out the entire understanding of the Parties with respect to the matters they purport to cover and supersede all prior communications, agreements, and understandings, whether written or oral, concerning such matters. No Party will be liable or bound to any Party in any manner by any warranties, representations, or covenants other than those set forth in or incorporated into this Agreement. The terms and conditions of this Agreement will inure to the benefit of and be binding upon the respective successors and permitted assigns of the Parties. Nothing in this Agreement, express or implied, is intended to confer upon any third party any rights, remedies, obligations, or liabilities under or by reason of this Agreement, except as expressly provided in this Agreement. Nothing in this Agreement is intended to modify the Wabash ILDSA, but this Agreement shall control to the extent it conflicts with the ILDSA. This Agreement does not supersede the Wabash ILDSA. 11.7. Forbearance and Waiver. Except where a specific time period is provided hereunder for the exercise of a right or remedy, any Partys forbearance in the exercise or enforcement of any right or remedy under this Agreement will not constitute a waiver thereof, and a waiver under one circumstance will not constitute a waiver under any other circumstance. 11.8. Partial Invalidity. Any invalidity, illegality, or unenforceability of any provision of this Agreement in any jurisdiction will not invalidate or render illegal or unenforceable the remaining provisions hereof in such jurisdiction and will not invalidate or render illegal or unenforceable such provision in any other jurisdiction. 11.9. No Implied Obligations. Neither the obligations nor the rights of either Party will be expanded beyond the terms of this Agreement on the basis of any legal or equitable principle or on any other basis whatsoever. Neither any equitable or legal principle nor any implied obligation of good faith or fair dealing nor any other matter requires any Party to perform, satisfy, or incur any act, condition, or obligation contrary to the terms of this Agreement, whether or not existing and whether foreseeable or unforeseeable. Each Party acknowledges that it would be unfair (and that it does not intend) to increase any of the obligations of the other Party under this Agreement on the basis of any implied obligation or otherwise. 11.10. Survival. Any provision specifically designated in this Agreement to survive the termination hereof and (unless otherwise expressly provided) any other provision which, by its nature, necessarily may become performable by a Party after termination of this Agreement will survive termination of this Agreement. 11.11. Governing Law; Venue; Waiver of Jury Trial. 11.11.1. Except as to matters preempted by the Constitution and statutes of the United States of America or regulations promulgated thereunder, this Agreement will be governed by, interpreted, construed, and enforced in accordance with the laws of the State of Indiana without regard to any conflict-of-law provisions that may refer to the laws of any other jurisdiction. After giving Page 12 effect to the preceding sentence, this Agreement is subject to all valid applicable federal, state, and local laws, ordinances, rules, and regulations of duly constituted regulatory authorities having jurisdiction. 11.11.2. The Parties hereby irrevocably submit to the exclusive jurisdiction of any state or federal court sitting in the State of Indiana in any action or proceeding arising out of, or relating to, this Agreement, and irrevocably agree that all claims in respect of such action or proceeding may be heard and determined in any such court. 11.11.3. Exhibit A Page 5 EXHIBIT B OPERATIONS SERVICES 1. SERVICES PROVIDED BY I&M I&M agrees to provide the following Operations Services to Wabash for the Meridian Substation. 1.1. Monitor, Operate and Dispatch Transmission System. I&M shall provide twenty-four (24) hour per day, seven (7) day per week monitoring of the Meridian Substation for safe and proper operation. I&M dispatchers shall take action as they deem appropriate to maintain the operation of the Meridian Substation within acceptable limits agreed to by the Parties. Such appropriate actions may include, but are not limited to, the scheduling and maintaining of transmission voltages utilizing Wabash owned reactive devices, and remote operation of switches and the breaker. 1.2. Supervisory Control and Data Acquisition. I&M will provide Supervisory Control and Data Acquisition (SCADA) services for the Meridian Substation, and I&M will provide the Operations Services solely via the SCADA system. 1.3. Coordination with PJM. I&M (through AEP System Operations) will manage communications, directives, and operating instructions with PJM as Transmission Operator to operate the Meridian Substation. 1.4. Ownership/Maintenance of Remote Terminal Unit. I&M will continue to own, maintain, and make necessary NERC filings for the Remote Terminal Unit for the Meridian Substation. 2. EXCLUDED SERVICES The Operations Services performed by I&M under this Agreement do not include the services listed in this Section 2. Wabash is responsible for arranging the following services for the Meridian Substation at its own cost. 2.1. Switching and Tagging. I&M will not provide on-site switching and tagging services for the Meridian Substation. Wabash is responsible for providing or designating a third party to provide switching and tagging services and for causing such third party to abide by the AEP Switching and Tagging Policies. 2.2. Maintenance and Periodic Inspections. Except as provided in Section 1.4 of this Exhibit B, I&M will not be responsible for maintenance nor periodic inspections of any equipment related to the Meridian Substation, which shall be solely the responsibility and at the sole cost of Wabash. 2.3. Planning & Operational Modeling Data. I&M will not be responsible for providing modeling data such as PSS/E Load Flow Data, EMS Modeling Data, etc.

Term and Termination. This Addendum shall be effective upon the Effective Date of the Agreement (the Addendum Effective Date) and shall continue until termination of the Agreement. Except as Wabash and I&M may otherwise agree in writing, the obligations, Exhibit C Page 1 duties, and powers specified in Section 3 shall survive termination of this Addendum for events occurring prior to termination. 3. Responsibilities and Obligations of the Parties a. Wabash has registered with the ERO, the RE, and PJM as a Transmission Owner for the Registered Facilities. I&M agrees (1) to provide NERC Compliance Support Services to Wabash for the Applicable Reliability Standards in regard to the Registered Facilities for the term of this Addendum; and (2) maintain, and provide to Wabash documentation directly related to the Registered Facilities which is reasonably necessary to support Wabash in complying with the Applicable Reliability Standards. The Parties agree that I&M has not and will not assume any NERC reporting obligation or responsibility for past or future compliance with any NERC Reliability Standard applicable to the Registered Facilities. b. Except as set forth on Appendix C to this Addendum, Wabash represents and warrants that there are no known unresolved or outstanding compliance monitoring or enforcement actions. While Wabash shall be solely responsible for resolution of all compliance matters related to the Registered Facilities, whether arising or discovered before or after the Effective date, I&M will assist and support Wabash with the resolution of any such matters as reasonably requested by Wabash, provided, however, that I&M does not assume any responsibility or accountability on behalf of Wabash for past or future NERC Compliance Obligations related to the Registered Facilities. c. I&M will assist Wabash in matters pertaining to compliance with the Applicable Reliability Standards for the Registered Facilities, including, but not limited to: 1) exchanging information related to compliance with the Applicable Reliability Standards; and (2) maintaining and providing books, records, and other information as to I&Ms operation of the Meridian Substation pursuant to the Agreement for purposes of responding to any inquiries, audits, investigations, enforcement actions, or claims from the ERO, the RE, the FERC, PJM, and/or other entities relating to compliance with the Applicable Reliability Standards. Although I&M will provide such assistance as outlined above, I&M does not assume any responsibility or accountability on behalf of Wabash for past or future NERC Compliance activities related to the Registered Facilities. d. Wabash shall be responsible for achieving compliance with the requirements of the Applicable Reliability Standards in regard to the Registered Facilities. Although I&M may agree to provide additional Compliance Support Exhibit C Page 2 Services as outlined in this paragraph, I&M does not assume any responsibility or accountability on behalf of Wabash for past or future NERC Compliance activities related to the Registered Facilities. e.
